b'' b'' b"| so, when you've got multi-tasking, you want to increase performance by" b'| increasing the amount of overlapping you do.' b'| b'| one way is with dma or bus mastering. either of these make it' b'| possible for i/o devices to move their data into and out of memory' b'| without interrupting the cpu. the alternative is for the cpu to move' b'| the data. there are several scsi interface cards that allow dma and' b'| bus mastering.' b'| b'| how do you do bus-mastering on the isa bus?' b'' b'as an earlier post noted through dma.' b'' b'| ide, however, is defined by the standard at interface' b'| created for the ibm pc at, which requires the cpu to move all the data' b'| bytes, with no dma.' b'' b"| if we're talking isa (at) bus here, then you can only have dma channel" b'| active at any one time, presumably transferring data from a single device.' b'| so even though you can have at least devices on a scsi bus, explain how' b'| all of those devices can to dma transfers through a single scsi card' b'| to the isa-at bus at the same time.' b'' b'any one time means imho a single byte xfer. if i have four sources of' b'dma requests ready, the dma would service the one after the other. if' b'the bandwidth for the four together is lower than the isa/dma' b'bandwidth, this will work.' b'' b'note that the bus mastering here is the priority mechanism in the dma' b'controller.' b'' b'--' b'' b'disclaimer: all oppinions are mine.' 